docs.abstract: The jurors in Glynn County, Ga., will resume deliberating on Wednesday. The three men accused of killing Ahmaud Arbery face charges of both malice murder and felony murder.
docs.snippet: The jurors in Glynn County, Ga., will resume deliberating on Wednesday. The three men accused of killing Ahmaud Arbery face charges of both malice murder and felony murder.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — A jury on Tuesday began deliberating on the fate of the three white men accused of murdering Ahmaud Arbery after hearing the final, impassioned argument of the lead prosecutor, Linda Dunikoski, who pushed back against the defense’s contention that the men had the legal right to pursue Mr. Arbery, and that the defendant Travis McMichael was acting in self-defense when he fatally shot him.

headline.main: Jury Begins Deliberations in Arbery Killing
headline.print_headline: After Prosecutor’s Rebuttal, Jury Begins Deliberations in Arbery Killing Trial

byline.original: By Richard Fausset, Rick Rojas and Tariro Mzezewa

docs.abstract: The prosecutor said Mr. Arbery had come “under attack.” Defense attorneys said their clients were justified in chasing him and trying to detain him.
docs.snippet: The prosecutor said Mr. Arbery had come “under attack.” Defense attorneys said their clients were justified in chasing him and trying to detain him.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — The trial of the three white men accused of murdering Ahmaud Arbery opened on Friday with the prosecution arguing that Mr. Arbery, a 25-year-old Black man, had come “under attack,” while defense attorneys said that their clients were justified in suspecting Mr. Arbery of burglary, chasing him in their trucks and trying to detain him until the police arrived.

headline.main: In Trial Opening, Two Starkly Different Views of Ahmaud Arbery’s Death
headline.print_headline: Starkly Conflicting Stories Open Arbery Murder Trial

byline.original: By Richard Fausset and Tariro Mzezewa

docs.abstract: Three white men were found guilty of murder and other charges on Wednesday for the pursuit and fatal shooting of Ahmaud Arbery, a 25-year-old Black man.

docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — Three white men were found guilty of murder and other charges on Wednesday for the pursuit and fatal shooting of Ahmaud Arbery, a 25-year-old Black man, in a case that, together with the killing of George Floyd, helped inspire the racial justice protests of last year.

headline.main: Three men are found guilty of murder in Arbery shooting.

docs.abstract: The three men who were found guilty of murdering Mr. Arbery are Travis McMichael, 35; his father, Gregory McMichael, 65; and their neighbor William Bryan, 52.

docs.snippet: On Thursday, Judge Timothy Walmsley heard several legal motions on what details of the Ahmaud Arbery case the jury will be allowed to hear.
docs.lead_paragraph: Judge Timothy R. Walmsley, who is presiding over the Ahmaud Arbery murder trial, ruled on a number of legal motions ahead of opening statements, including allowing into evidence video images from the body camera of a responding police officer who hovered over Mr. Arbery after he was shot.

headline.main: The judge rules on several pretrial motions in favor of the prosecution.

docs.abstract: Ministers asked Brunswick, Ga., to remain peaceful despite unhappiness that a nearly all-white jury had been seated in the trial of the white men accused of killing Ahmaud Arbery, a Black man.
docs.snippet: Ministers asked Brunswick, Ga., to remain peaceful despite unhappiness that a nearly all-white jury had been seated in the trial of the white men accused of killing Ahmaud Arbery, a Black man.
docs.lead_paragraph: A group of clergy members gathered outside the Glynn County Superior Court in Brunswick, Ga., on Friday morning, urging the community to remain peaceful and united despite their unhappiness that a nearly all-white jury had been seated in the trial of the white men accused of killing Ahmaud Arbery, a Black man.

headline.main: ‘We serve a God who is not asleep’: Clergy members urge unity for Ahmaud Arbery’s family.

docs.abstract: He signed up to be a cadet in a program for teenagers who aspire to be police officers. He filled his Facebook page with support for Blue Lives Matter. He sat up front at a rally for President Donald J. Trump, and posted images of it on TikTok. And he chose to mark his 16th birthday by raising funds for a support group for the police called Humanizing the Badge.

docs.lead_paragraph: The lead prosecutor in the trial of the three white men accused of murdering Ahmaud Arbery said in her opening statement on Friday that Mr. Arbery was plainly “under attack” by the defendants when they chased him in trucks through their neighborhood — a chase that ended with one of the defendants, Travis McMichael, fatally shooting Mr. Arbery with his pump-action shotgun.

headline.main: In her opening statement, the lead prosecutor says Ahmaud Arbery was ‘under attack.’
